<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>Vibhu's Blog</title><link>https://pwsh.in/</link><description>Recent content on Vibhu's Blog</description><generator>Hugo -- gohugo.io</generator><language>en</language><lastBuildDate>Sun, 22 Mar 2026 10:00:00 +0530</lastBuildDate><atom:link href="https://pwsh.in/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title>Automating Azure AD Sync Monitoring Across 155 MSP Clients with PowerShell</title><link>https://pwsh.in/posts/automating-ad-sync-monitoring-with-powershell/</link><pubDate>Sun, 22 Mar 2026 10:00:00 +0530</pubDate><guid>https://pwsh.in/posts/automating-ad-sync-monitoring-with-powershell/</guid><description>&lt;p>Managing Azure AD Connect sync health across a single tenant is straightforward. Doing it across
155+ MSP clients simultaneously — where each has its own Azure AD tenant, its own sync schedule,
and its own failure modes — is a different problem entirely.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>This post covers how I built a monitoring tool that solved this for our team, cutting what used
to be a daily manual check into something that runs automatically and only pages us when something
actually needs attention.&lt;/p></description></item><item><title/><link>https://pwsh.in/notes/powershell/basics/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://pwsh.in/notes/powershell/basics/</guid><description>&lt;div class="note-card ">
